This paper discusses the structure and behavior of convolutional neural networks (CNNs) and proposes a mathematical model to explain their properties. The focus is on image classification tasks, which are typically addressed in the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper also discusses the training process and the importance of non-linear activation functions, which are relevant to machine learning (cs.LG) and neural networks (cs.NE). The use of the MNIST dataset and the LeNet-5 and AlexNet architectures suggests a focus on artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and deep learning (cs.SI). Overall, cs.CV is the most likely sub-category, followed by cs.LG, cs.NE, cs.AI, and cs.SI.
